Package io.github.ai4ci.config.inhost

Interface PhenomenologicalModel

All Superinterfaces:
DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological<Distribution,Double>, InHostConfiguration, Serializable
@Immutable public interface PhenomenologicalModel extends InHostConfiguration, DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological<Distribution,Double>
Configuration for an in‑host phenomenological model.

This interface captures the distributions and thresholds used by the phenomenological in‑host model. It includes parameters for incubation, timing of peak viral load and recovery, approximate peak viral load and immune response, and immune waning.

Several entries are subject to demographic adjustment via DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological and may be modified at runtime by the execution configuration. In particular the following getters are adjustable by demographic factors:

  • getIncubationPeriod()
  • getPeakToRecoveryDelay()
  • getImmuneWaningHalfLife()

Downstream uses include the initialiser DefaultInHostPhenomenologicalStateInitialiser which samples these distributions to build an InHostPhenomenologicalState. It is also referenced by example code and tests.

Author:
Rob Challen

  • Field Details

    • DEFAULT

      static final io.github.ai4ci.config.inhost.ImmutablePhenomenologicalModel DEFAULT
      A sensible default parameterisation of the phenomenological model.

      The default values provide a compact set of distributions used in examples and tests. Downstream callers that rely on this simple default include the default in‑host phenomenological initialiser and example experiments.

      See Also:
      • DefaultInHostPhenomenologicalStateInitialiser

  • Method Details

    • getApproxPeakImmuneResponse

      Distribution getApproxPeakImmuneResponse()
      Approximate distribution for peak immune response.

      This is used in the phenomenological immune model to determine the amplitude of the host immune response and its effect on viral decay. It is not adjusted via the demographic adjustment interface in the standard configuration.

      Returns:
      the peak immune response

    • getApproxPeakViralLoad

      Distribution getApproxPeakViralLoad()
      Approximate distribution for peak viral load or its proxy.

      This value is used to calibrate the shape and amplitude of the viral load trajectory. It is not directly adjusted by the demographic adjustment component in the current design.

      Returns:
      the peak viral load

    • getImmuneWaningHalfLife

      Distribution getImmuneWaningHalfLife()
      Distribution for the half life of waning immunity.

      This parameter may be adjusted by DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological implementations to represent age dependent differences in immune waning. Callers such as initialisers and immune decay updaters sample this distribution when computing immunity loss over time.

      Specified by:
      getImmuneWaningHalfLife in interface DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological<Distribution,Double>
      Returns:
      the immune waning half life

    • getIncubationPeriod

      Distribution getIncubationPeriod()
      Distribution for the incubation period (time from infection to onset).

      This distribution is sampled by the default initialiser and by the viral load calibration code. It is adjustable by DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological implementations, allowing age dependent scaling of incubation timing.

      Specified by:
      getIncubationPeriod in interface DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological<Distribution,Double>
      Returns:
      the incubation periods

    • getIncubationToPeakViralLoadDelay

      Distribution getIncubationToPeakViralLoadDelay()
      Delay from incubation/onset to peak viral load.

      This distribution is sampled when constructing the viral load model for an infected individual. It is not listed as adjustable in the DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological interface and so remains constant across demographic groups unless modified elsewhere.

      Returns:
      the delay from onset to peak viral load

    • getInfectiousnessCutoff

      Double getInfectiousnessCutoff()
      Cutoff of the viral load or proxy used to determine infectiousness.

      Value is used by initialisers and state code to determine whether an individual is infectious at a given point on their viral load curve.

      Returns:
      infectiousness cutoff in the unit interval

    • getPeakImmuneResponseDelay

      Distribution getPeakImmuneResponseDelay()
      Delay from infection/onset to peak immune response.

      This distribution is sampled when creating an individual's immune response trajectory and is used by the viral load/immune interaction routines.

      Returns:
      the delay to peak immune response

    • getPeakToRecoveryDelay

      Distribution getPeakToRecoveryDelay()
      Delay from peak viral load to recovery.

      The DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological may adjust this value via the getPeakToRecoveryDelay entry in certain demographic configurations; callers should consult the execution configuration's demographic adjustment before sampling if age dependent values are required.

      Specified by:
      getPeakToRecoveryDelay in interface DemographicAdjustment.Phenomenological<Distribution,Double>
      Returns:
      the delay from peak to recovery
